ative features. It follows that investigating evaluative morphology in sign languages (SLs) can enrich the literature and offer new insights. This book provides descriptive and theoretical contributions by considering Italian Sign Language (LIS) as empirical ground of investigation. At the descriptive level, the analysis of corpus and elicited data improves the description of morphological processes in LIS, as well as typological studies on evaluative morphology by adding the patterns of a visuo-gestural language. At the theoretical level, the study shows the benefit of combining different approaches (Generative Linguistics, Linguistic Typology, Cognitive Linguistics) for the exploration of evaluative constructions in SLs, as it allows to identify both modality-specific and modality-independent properties.In sum, this book encourages the readers to rely on different data types, analyses and theoretical perspectives to investigate linguistic phenomena in SLs.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGebärdensprache. 4aLIS. 4aLingua dei Segni Italiana. 4aMorphologie. 4aNonmanuelle Zeichen. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Sign Language.2bisacsh  aEvaluative Morphology.  aItalian Sign Language.  aNon-manual Markers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2023 Englishz978311131916208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2023z9783111318240oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97831107835060 cprintz978311078339140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311078344540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110783445423Coveruhttps://www.degruyte